
CumuloFS

* Inode Re-Use
   - Assume file deleted then immediately re-created w/ same Inode
   - Reads of old pointer will fail with InvalidObject
   - if we fall back to the InodeTable, it'll succeed due to the new pointer stored there w/ correct type

* Treat InodePointer as authoritative source of Inode type.
   - Set at allocation time
   - Never modified
* Update Inode to force the mode to contain the correct time in mode accesser method

* Create an Inode hierarchy
   DirectoryInode & FileInode have differing Keys
   Constructor asserts on Inode pointer type... Should we have a hierarchy of these too?

** Need to store parent directory inode in directory inodes
  allows lookup of ".." from a directory
  hardlinks are not allowed for dirs anyway

* must be able to lookup parent node ids
* When looking up a directory _entry_, we're given the parent directory inode
* FUSE_CREATE is used to create missing files/dirs unless it returns ENOSYS. Then mknod + open are used
  mknod
   name of the file trails the header
   the rdev param is a dev_t and is set only if the mode indicates a device file
     |-> From the filesystem layer, we should be able to ignore the format of the content. Just store 
         and send back when asked

** Throw out the idea of relocating Inodes. Should be easy to impl later if really needed. 
  - Use the table when we have only an inode
  - Direct readObject when we have the pointer

** For now read entire directory in a single shot - Do this in OpenDirectory
  - should work fine for fuse
  - can impl the more complex logic later
  - Directory just holds an array of DirEntry
  
** First file impl should read all file pointers as well.
  - Maybe make the management of file pointers a Mixin trait for OpenDirectory/OpenFile?

What does a directory need to do?
  * Provide basic attributes (supplied by Inode)
  * Provide access to Name -> (Inode,Pointer) content
  * Provide Transaction method to insert Name -> (Inode,Pointer)
    - Main func should take a MutableNode (allows caching impl on frontend)
     - If Name already exists,
         * Tx requirement for exact mactch on timestamp
         * Decref object as part of insertion
         * incref inode object
     - If Name does not exist
         * Tx requiement for not exist
         * Incref inode object


* Implement ls -l on root directory
   * load directory instance
   * opendir support -> returns OpenDir
   * readdir support
      - internal fileHandle (incr by 1 for each entry read & maintain copy of last key to resume from)
      - if read request on open dir does not resume from previous file descriptor location,
        drop cached location. Count entries from beginning and resume from that location.

Skipping all caching would certainly make things simpler.
Probably the right way to go for the first-pass impl
Always reading from the backend ensures consistency
Calls to CumuloFS essentially mean the Kernel NEEDS to query the backend anyway
   |-> can leave caching to the kernel
Open Files/Dirs cache only Immutable data and pointers. Revision checks are used
to ensure out-of-date pointers are used safely

*** Should we have a separate OpenFile OpenDirectory set of classes?
    - Each references a File/Directory
    - Holds file handle and implements what little handle-specific stuff there is
    - Leaves the rest to the File/Directory
       - which can use synchronized methods to prevent race conditions

*** For multiple reads, can capture the read initiation time in a closure. When the result
    becomes available, check the cached version. If it's newer, update the cached copy and
    return the read version. If the cached copy is newer (race condition, return that instead)

DirectoryLoader -> FSEntryLoader
  - Loads an FSEntity (File, Directory, Symlink, etc)
      - Hasa Inode as private var attribute
      - Provides synchronized methods to:
         - get current Inode
         - refreshInode (multiple calls return same future)
      - How do we keep this up to date?
         - Essentially we cannot cache mutable inode content :(
         - No way to know the order of delta application
         - External entity could change it at any time
      - We CAN cache things like data and xattr tree roots though (e.g. Pointers)
         - perf suffers if another peer does updates but we can periodically re-read the
           inode if an access occurs after root has been cached for X num seconds
         - Open file handle can cache tier-1 end node during write
            - With fixed-size blocks, we could use key-doesnt-exist requiements
            - Might be better to always use version requirements 
      - When FSEntity is obtained from InodeLoader, do not refreshInode to respond to queries
      - if pulled from cache, DO refreshInode content before responding
          |--- Then what's the point of having a cache at all?

InodeLoader
   - Synchronized Object that loads (inodePointer) -> Future[Inode]
   - First access creates future. Subsequent calls return same future.
   - On complete, future is removed from loading map (this isn't a cache)

Create File Task impl (zero data. open must succeed before data can be written)
   - must have target directory. start with root

File & Directory classes
  |=> File class only applies to an Open file for read/write
      it Has A inode
  |=> Dir class is similar but we modify it without first opening it...
      so we may want a cache of Directory instances? 
      Create on demand and discard after last operation completes?

caching
  write-through: (aka DirectIO) Data -> cache -> device then return
  write-around: Data -> device then return
  write-back: Data -> mem. Return. Background -> device
  
  * Even with write-back, files can be opened w/ DirectIO

